00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:26.930
the emails from the other side
onto the blogosphere, right?

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:29.460
in order to embarrass
them in between meetings.

00:45:29.460 --> 00:45:31.042
I mean, it was brutal.

00:45:31.042 --> 00:45:31.875
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:45:31.875 --> 00:45:33.203
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes, sir.

00:45:33.203 --> 00:45:35.070
AUDIENCE: Hi,
Governor Richardson.

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:38.570
So have you ever like
been in such a situation

00:45:38.570 --> 00:45:41.570
that when you're trying to
make a personal connection

00:45:41.570 --> 00:45:45.250
with a dictator you're trying to
be humorous and telling a joke

00:45:45.250 --> 00:45:47.370
but the other one just
didn't get, and feel

00:45:47.370 --> 00:45:50.060
like you're too personal.

00:45:50.060 --> 00:45:53.660
Have you met the situation,
and how you would deal with it?

00:45:53.660 --> 00:45:54.160
GOV.

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:56.620
BILL RICHARDSON: Well, you
know, the North Koreans,

00:45:56.620 --> 00:45:58.380
they don't think like we do.

00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:02.290
We believe the
concept of negotiation

00:46:02.290 --> 00:46:03.800
is the quid pro quo.

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:04.570
You do something.

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:05.710
I do something.

00:46:05.710 --> 00:46:07.770
The North Koreans
don't believe in that.

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:11.790
They believe that their
position is the right one.

00:46:11.790 --> 00:46:15.180
And the concession they make
is, they'll give you a few weeks

00:46:15.180 --> 00:46:16.410
to come to their position.

00:46:16.410 --> 00:46:18.130
That they're concession.

00:46:18.130 --> 00:46:21.150
And when you have that
mindset against you,

00:46:21.150 --> 00:46:23.530
remember this is a
cult of personality,

00:46:23.530 --> 00:46:26.475
you've got to be careful
sometimes about the humor.

00:46:26.475 --> 00:46:30.380
You know, with North
Korea, Eric, these guys,

00:46:30.380 --> 00:46:33.470
we try to be as
serious as we can.

00:46:33.470 --> 00:46:35.510
We want to drive home a message.

00:46:35.510 --> 00:46:38.480
You want to be candid,
but at the same time,

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:43.050
so I won't say you delete the
humor from the North Koreans,

00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:48.266
but you're selective
in how you use it.

00:46:48.266 --> 00:46:50.140
KEVIN BLEYER: They
weren't totally humorless.

00:46:50.140 --> 00:46:51.942
One of the last
nights we were there,

00:46:51.942 --> 00:46:56.290
there was a moment when I
think maybe Jared had said

00:46:56.290 --> 00:47:00.070
to the woman who they called
the Condi Rice of North Korea,

00:47:00.070 --> 00:47:02.890
Kevin actually has been a
writer for "The Daily Show."

00:47:02.890 --> 00:47:03.990
Her eyes lit up.

00:47:03.990 --> 00:47:06.180
She said, Jon Stewart?

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:09.412
Next time you come you
have to bring him with you.

00:47:09.412 --> 00:47:10.370
I thought two thoughts.

00:47:10.370 --> 00:47:12.494
One, next time I come,
is that an invitation,

00:47:12.494 --> 00:47:13.910
and the second
thought is, I don't

00:47:13.910 --> 00:47:15.770
think Jon Stewart would
come to North Korea.

00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:16.520
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:47:16.520 --> 00:47:17.090
Yes, sir.

00:47:17.090 --> 00:47:20.060
AUDIENCE: I was just taking
a few pages on your chapter

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:24.600
on Venezuelan, your interactions
with Hugo Chavez including

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:26.560
one of the first defining
moments of the US

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:28.100
and Venezuelan
relationship, which

00:47:28.100 --> 00:47:31.910
was his first visit
to the White House.

00:47:31.910 --> 00:47:34.840
But aside from your
experience with the bad guy,

00:47:34.840 --> 00:47:39.790
can you elaborate more on
mistakes done by other US

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:44.326
officials along those 14 years
of really bad relationship?

00:47:44.326 --> 00:47:44.826
GOV.

00:47:44.826 --> 00:47:48.750
BILL RICHARDSON: Well,
my view with Hugo Chavez

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:53.410
is encapsulated in the thought
that our policy towards him

00:47:53.410 --> 00:47:56.090
was basically ignore him.

00:47:56.090 --> 00:47:57.115
This was US policy.

00:47:57.115 --> 00:47:59.890
It was almost stated.

00:47:59.890 --> 00:48:03.270
I think that was a
mistake, Clinton, Bush.

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:04.180
And you're right.

00:48:04.180 --> 00:48:07.470
I went to his inaugural when
he was first made president.

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:12.380
He was insulted that I went and
not President Clinton or Gore.

00:48:12.380 --> 00:48:15.070
So that was like his first--
I won't say that was decisive.

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:23.550
So I think ignoring
somebody doesn't make sense.

00:48:23.550 --> 00:48:25.880
I think eventually
you have to engage.

00:48:25.880 --> 00:48:27.660
I always feel that
Latin America is

00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:30.140
a part of the world we
should pay more attention to.

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:33.150
But right now, you know our
relations with Venezuela

00:48:33.150 --> 00:48:34.530
is not good.

00:48:34.530 --> 00:48:36.940
Our relations with
Nicaragua is not good,

00:48:36.940 --> 00:48:39.750
with Cuba, it's not good,
with Bolivia, it's not good.

00:48:39.750 --> 00:48:42.300
We barely have
ambassadors there.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:44.310
With Ecuador, it's not good.

00:48:44.310 --> 00:48:49.480
So ignoring is a
policy option, but I

00:48:49.480 --> 00:48:55.890
would prefer engaging, engaging
in technology interactions,

00:48:55.890 --> 00:48:57.850
and academic interactions.

00:48:57.850 --> 00:49:01.540
And once in awhile have the
Secretary of State visit

00:49:01.540 --> 00:49:03.480
even if there are differences.

00:49:03.480 --> 00:49:06.290
I think that only
inflames a country more.

00:49:06.290 --> 00:49:09.430
With Venezuela, I
was at the election

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:12.390
of the new president, Maduro.

00:49:12.390 --> 00:49:16.100
I don't know if he really
won. it was so close.

00:49:16.100 --> 00:49:19.960
But he reached out to me
knowing that I was an America

00:49:19.960 --> 00:49:23.480
and I was an observer of the
organization of Americans.

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:26.230
And he sent a message,
well, I'd like

00:49:26.230 --> 00:49:29.160
to improve the
relationship with the US.

00:49:29.160 --> 00:49:32.490
And this guy, Maduro,
he's not like Chavez was.

00:49:32.490 --> 00:49:34.680
Chavez was very strong.

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:37.660
His people believed in him.

00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:40.760
And the problem with
Maduro, a few days

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:46.060
after, he says to the
world, I'll take Snowden.

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:47.030
He's in Russia.

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:48.510
I'll let him come in.

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:50.390
By the way, this
may not be popular.

00:49:50.390 --> 00:49:52.970
I'm not a big fan of
Snowden, what he did.

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:55.610
I mean, that's the National
Security of the United States.

00:49:55.610 --> 00:49:58.690
For him to decide he's going
to release what's right

00:49:58.690 --> 00:50:01.370
and what's wrong, I
think that's wrong.

00:50:01.370 --> 00:50:03.650
But did I answer your question?

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:04.540
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:04.540 --> 00:50:05.040
GOV.

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:05.430
BILL RICHARDSON: Thank you.

00:50:05.430 --> 00:50:05.816
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:50:05.816 --> 00:50:06.316
Yes, sir.

00:50:06.316 --> 00:50:09.120
AUDIENCE: Governor Richardson,
