the Chinese citizens

00:50:30.246 --> 00:50:30.746
GOV.

00:50:30.746 --> 00:50:32.120
BILL RICHARDSON:
Yeah, but, Eric,

00:50:32.120 --> 00:50:36.280
guys fixed that problem,
didn't you or not?

00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:37.790
Didn't we not?

00:50:37.790 --> 00:50:40.080
I know you're pushing
it, but wasn't there

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:41.700
some progress on that or not?

00:50:41.700 --> 00:50:42.846
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:50:42.846 --> 00:50:46.180
ERIC SCHMIDT: I think
it's on negotiation,

00:50:46.180 --> 00:50:47.630
and we're losing it.

00:50:47.630 --> 00:50:48.470
KEVIN BLEYER: Perhaps
they need a mediator.

00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:48.970
GOV.

00:50:48.970 --> 00:50:54.830
BILL RICHARDSON: You know,
look, we should not fear China.

00:50:54.830 --> 00:50:58.700
You know, American politics,
oh, every campaign, the Chinese,

00:50:58.700 --> 00:51:00.790
bah, bah, bah.

00:51:00.790 --> 00:51:06.300
First, we should think of China
as a strategic competitor.

00:51:06.300 --> 00:51:09.530
We should also think of
China as a country that

00:51:09.530 --> 00:51:12.870
is trying to decide
where it wants to go.

00:51:12.870 --> 00:51:16.830
When I was at the UN, they
were already a major power.

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:19.120
They only paid 3% of the budget.

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:21.070
We paid 28% of the UN.

00:51:21.070 --> 00:51:23.180
And they'd say, well,
we're a developing country.

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:25.760
We can't afford more than 3%.

00:51:25.760 --> 00:51:29.100
Now, they're paying more
now, but they still, I

00:51:29.100 --> 00:51:31.410
don't think they've
decided in terms

00:51:31.410 --> 00:51:33.584
of their great
economic power what

00:51:33.584 --> 00:51:34.750
they're going to do with it.

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:35.730
That's my theory.

00:51:35.730 --> 00:51:37.160
I may be wrong.

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:41.860
My point is that the
American-Chinese relationship

00:51:41.860 --> 00:51:44.310
has a lot of different handles.

00:51:44.310 --> 00:51:47.800
There's the North Korea side,
the national security side,

00:51:47.800 --> 00:51:51.680
military presence in East
Asia, the technology side,

00:51:51.680 --> 00:51:53.380
the trade side they control.

00:51:53.380 --> 00:51:56.240
They spoke out on the shut down.

00:51:56.240 --> 00:51:59.660
They were worried about
their investments in the US.

00:51:59.660 --> 00:52:02.700
So we have to be very
careful in this relationship

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:05.900
and know that it has
a lot of branches.

00:52:05.900 --> 00:52:08.170
And when you start
insulting each other,

00:52:08.170 --> 00:52:12.620
the Chinese are very
big on saving face,

00:52:12.620 --> 00:52:15.980
on decorum, on proper channels.

00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:20.020
I wouldn't use too
much humor with them

00:52:20.020 --> 00:52:22.300
if I were negotiating with them.

00:52:22.300 --> 00:52:25.660
But I think on the technology
side, one of the things

00:52:25.660 --> 00:52:28.840
that the Chinese will say at
the end of the conference,

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:30.810
I know Eric goes
to a lot of them

00:52:30.810 --> 00:52:35.990
like I do as does Kevin, is
the Chinese will blast us

00:52:35.990 --> 00:52:38.620
at the conference,
Davos, anywhere.

00:52:38.620 --> 00:52:40.880
But then at the end
of the conference,

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:42.030
this is what they say.

00:52:42.030 --> 00:52:43.310
They say, OK.

00:52:43.310 --> 00:52:48.770
America, clean up your
act, but lead, lead.

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:50.610
What I'm trying to
say is that I think

00:52:50.610 --> 00:52:53.790
we just continue
these discussions.

00:52:53.790 --> 00:52:56.830
I think the negotiation on
cyber security between the two

00:52:56.830 --> 00:52:59.510
countries are
enormously important.

00:52:59.510 --> 00:53:02.940
And it's better to try to
make agreements with them

00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:05.250
while their policies
are evolving,

00:53:05.250 --> 00:53:09.440
and I think they're trying to
decide where they want to go.

00:53:09.440 --> 00:53:10.856
Eric, what's your
thought on that?

00:53:10.856 --> 00:53:13.040
ERIC SCHMIDT: I
actually agree with you.

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:15.875
Let's have these be the
two final questions,

00:53:15.875 --> 00:53:17.500
and then we'll have
a wrap-up question,

00:53:17.500 --> 00:53:18.458
and then we'll be done.

00:53:18.458 --> 00:53:19.295
Yes, sir.

