And right now the Tea Party
Republicans in the house

00:55:56.970 --> 00:56:01.276
are adamantly opposed to any
changes in the immigration law,

00:56:01.276 --> 00:56:03.400
and that's going to hurt
them with Cuban Americans,

00:56:03.400 --> 00:56:06.100
with Mexican Americans,
Central Americans that

00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:10.457
are part of this American
political fabric.

00:56:10.457 --> 00:56:11.290
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:56:11.290 --> 00:56:12.289
ERIC SCHMIDT: Thank you.

00:56:12.289 --> 00:56:14.200
And our final question.

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:16.490
AUDIENCE: Governor
Richardson, I would just

00:56:16.490 --> 00:56:19.910
like to ask you on a comment
on the situation in Syria,

00:56:19.910 --> 00:56:22.620
how the ongoing
negotiations don't

00:56:22.620 --> 00:56:24.850
seem to bring much in
the whole situation

00:56:24.850 --> 00:56:27.790
with attack and not attacking.

00:56:27.790 --> 00:56:29.130
What's your view on this?

00:56:29.130 --> 00:56:29.630
GOV.

00:56:29.630 --> 00:56:33.620
BILL RICHARDSON:
Well, God, I love,

00:56:33.620 --> 00:56:37.620
besides my love for
Google, I love Facebook.

00:56:37.620 --> 00:56:42.770
I love to read all the comments
on Twitter on this issue.

00:56:42.770 --> 00:56:48.540
I came out saying I support
Obama in the military strikes.

00:56:48.540 --> 00:56:49.250
Why?

00:56:49.250 --> 00:56:52.780
Because I think there has
to be a consequence of cost

00:56:52.780 --> 00:56:55.970
when there's a violation
of human rights of chemical

00:56:55.970 --> 00:56:57.190
weapons used.

00:56:57.190 --> 00:56:59.270
I think it's an
international crime.

00:56:59.270 --> 00:57:02.640
Now, I'm not for
intervening with boots

00:57:02.640 --> 00:57:05.280
on the ground and
more than that.

00:57:05.280 --> 00:57:08.220
So I thought that
was a right response.

00:57:08.220 --> 00:57:10.150
Now, what has happened since?

00:57:10.150 --> 00:57:12.770
Right now, everybody
dumps on the UN.

00:57:12.770 --> 00:57:16.470
But you know who's enforcing
the chemical weapons ban, which

00:57:16.470 --> 00:57:18.380
I think is going
to happen in Syria?

00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:19.310
The UN.

00:57:19.310 --> 00:57:21.210
Who won the Nobel Prize?

00:57:21.210 --> 00:57:23.830
The chemical weapons
investigators.

00:57:23.830 --> 00:57:25.210
They won the Nobel.

00:57:25.210 --> 00:57:28.330
I think that Pakistani
woman should have won it.

00:57:28.330 --> 00:57:29.430
But apart from that--

00:57:29.430 --> 00:57:29.680
KEVIN BLEYER: Malala.

00:57:29.680 --> 00:57:29.757
GOV.

00:57:29.757 --> 00:57:30.600
BILL RICHARDSON:
The little girl.

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:31.190
What's her name?

00:57:31.190 --> 00:57:31.996
KEVIN BLEYER: Malala.

00:57:31.996 --> 00:57:32.097
GOV.

00:57:32.097 --> 00:57:33.013
BILL RICHARDSON: Yeah.

00:57:33.013 --> 00:57:33.670
I mean, jeez.

00:57:33.670 --> 00:57:37.380
This little girl was
such a great symbol.

00:57:37.380 --> 00:57:42.260
So what I think is going
to happen in Syria,

00:57:42.260 --> 00:57:45.530
I think Russia, and I'm
being generous here,

00:57:45.530 --> 00:57:49.110
I think Russia realizes
that Assad is a loser.

00:57:49.110 --> 00:57:50.740
He's going to go down.

00:57:50.740 --> 00:57:52.110
He's not popular.

00:57:52.110 --> 00:57:54.780
His own military, I believe,
is going to take him down.

00:57:54.780 --> 00:57:57.030
Now, a lot of people
disagree with me.

00:57:57.030 --> 00:58:00.560
They say, oh, you know,
nothing is going to change.

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:01.980
Obama made a mistake.

00:58:01.980 --> 00:58:06.410
I think we were actually
lucky that what happened

00:58:06.410 --> 00:58:11.630
was an opportunity that the
Russians presented saying, OK.

00:58:11.630 --> 00:58:13.610
What if we get rid of
all the chemical weapons?

00:58:13.610 --> 00:58:15.910
Will this deter the
military strike?

00:58:15.910 --> 00:58:19.930
And of that negotiation
leads to a negotiation

00:58:19.930 --> 00:58:23.950
on the future of Assad on
a political transition,

00:58:23.950 --> 00:58:26.250
I think it's a major
accomplishment.

00:58:26.250 --> 00:58:29.380
But the situation is unstable.

00:58:29.380 --> 00:58:31.760
There's no question about it.

00:58:31.760 --> 00:58:35.810
But I think the Russians know
that this guy Assad is a loser.

00:58:35.810 --> 00:58:40.250
So if they are maneuvering to
have a political transition

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:42.960
after the chemical
weapons are banned,

00:58:42.960 --> 00:58:45.290
and I believe the
inspectors will make sure

00:58:45.290 --> 00:58:46.360
that does happen.

00:58:46.360 --> 00:58:47.850
You know, everybody's a cynic.

00:58:47.850 --> 00:58:49.330
Oh, it's not going to happen.

00:58:49.330 --> 00:58:52.230
I'm an optimist by nature.

00:58:52.230 --> 00:58:53.510
Do you disagree?

00:58:53.510 --> 00:58:54.400
AUDIENCE: No.

00:58:54.400 --> 00:58:54.900
GOV.

00:58:54.900 --> 00:58:55.735
BILL RICHARDSON: No?

00:58:55.735 --> 00:58:56.870
ERIC SCHMIDT: Kevin?

00:58:56.870 --> 00:58:58.029
He's negotiating.

00:58:58.029 --> 00:58:58.820
KEVIN BLEYER: Yeah.

00:58:58.820 --> 00:58:59.320
Right.

00:58:59.320 --> 00:59:01.250
ERIC SCHMIDT: Kevin.

00:59:01.250 --> 00:59:05.175
after the successful book tour,
what are you going to do next?

00:59:05.175 --> 00:59:06.819
KEVIN BLEYER: That's
a good question.

00:59:06.819 --> 00:59:08.485
I don't know how to
live this down or up

00:59:08.485 --> 00:59:12.050
or what have you after traveling
the world with the two of you

00:59:12.050 --> 00:59:13.810
and also feeling
like I've traveled

00:59:13.810 --> 00:59:16.310
the world for the last three
decades and sitting at his knee

00:59:16.310 --> 00:59:18.170
and learning all the
negotiations he's

00:59:18.170 --> 00:59:19.710
had with these amazing people.

00:59:19.710 --> 00:59:21.430
I feel like I've
lived there too.

00:59:21.430 --> 00:59:23.687
I was in those rooms and
hopefully, the book as well

00:59:23.687 --> 00:59:24.770
gives you a sense of that.

00:59:24.770 --> 00:59:26.644
So quite frankly, I'm
a little bit exhausted.

00:59:26.644 --> 00:59:28.060
I'll be honest with you.

00:59:28.060 --> 00:59:33.560
Next I feel like there's---
I'm told that political satire

00:59:33.560 --> 00:59:36.850
to some degree, the fake news
world is the growth industry--

00:59:36.850 --> 00:59:39.580
ERIC SCHMIDT: They have
generated so much new material

00:59:39.580 --> 00:59:40.080
for you.

00:59:40.080 --> 00:59:40.690
KEVIN BLEYER: So
apparently, yeah.

00:59:40.690 --> 00:59:42.898
I'm going to keep pursuing
that and see what happens.

00:59:42.898 --> 00:59:45.480
ERIC SCHMIDT: Governor,
after this is over,

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:48.280
you have a foundation
you've been heavily engaged,

00:59:48.280 --> 00:59:49.720
I know, in Cuban issues.

00:59:49.720 --> 00:59:53.643
What do you think your
next negotiation is?

00:59:53.643 --> 00:59:54.143
GOV.

00:59:54.143 --> 00:59:57.360
BILL RICHARDSON: Right
now, I believe, by the way,

00:59:57.360 --> 01:00:01.090
I formed a foundation
with Robert Redford.

01:00:01.090 --> 01:00:05.840
I am passionate about protecting
wild horses and mustangs.

01:00:05.840 --> 01:00:08.690
And there's a move afoot
to start slaughtering them

01:00:08.690 --> 01:00:09.940
because they're proliferating.

01:00:09.940 --> 01:00:11.710
There's no question about it.

01:00:11.710 --> 01:00:14.700
I just negotiated an agreement
with the Navajo nation,

01:00:14.700 --> 01:00:17.810
which had announced
a policy of killing

01:00:17.810 --> 01:00:20.460
these horses because they
were overrunning the Navajo

01:00:20.460 --> 01:00:21.640
reservation.

01:00:21.640 --> 01:00:26.780
So in exchange for them not
doing this, the Navajos,

01:00:26.780 --> 01:00:30.940
we're providing what is
called PCP, birth control,

01:00:30.940 --> 01:00:33.110
sanctuaries for the horses.

01:00:33.110 --> 01:00:37.840
So I have this other foundation,
the international foundation.

01:00:37.840 --> 01:00:41.740
We specialize in trying to
get political prisoners out.

01:00:41.740 --> 01:00:44.920
We specialize in relations
with difficult countries,

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:50.560
like North Korea, training
the legislature where

01:00:50.560 --> 01:00:52.690
Eric Schmidt's daughter
helped us train

01:00:52.690 --> 01:00:56.350
the legislature in
Burma on technology.

01:00:56.350 --> 01:00:59.050
But apart from that,
Eric, right now,

01:00:59.050 --> 01:01:05.410
I've been 32 years in the
public sector in government.

01:01:05.410 --> 01:01:06.430
I do speeches.

01:01:06.430 --> 01:01:08.180
I've got a speaker's bureau.

01:01:08.180 --> 01:01:09.680
I serve on boards.

01:01:09.680 --> 01:01:16.180
I have a relationship with
this PR firm called APCO.

01:01:16.180 --> 01:01:19.700
But I stay involved
in the policy.

01:01:19.700 --> 01:01:21.420
I'm a defender of the president.

01:01:21.420 --> 01:01:24.670
I think he's done
a good job on TV.

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:31.240
And my last point is, I'm
making a little money.

01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:32.920
OK?

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:35.060
And Eric, my taxes are too high.

01:01:35.060 --> 01:01:36.245
What do we do about it?

01:01:36.245 --> 01:01:37.170
ERIC SCHMIDT: Kevin.

01:01:37.170 --> 01:01:39.440
KEVIN BLEYER: There's
one, I would be remiss.

01:01:39.440 --> 01:01:40.237
Forgive me.

01:01:40.237 --> 01:01:42.820
I would not let this opportunity
go by in this particular day.

01:01:42.820 --> 01:01:44.650
As I stare across
Governor Richardson

01:01:44.650 --> 01:01:46.970
and see you across
the way to not

01:01:46.970 --> 01:01:48.921
tell this very quick anecdote.

01:01:48.921 --> 01:01:51.170
That this is the only place
I would be able to tell it

01:01:51.170 --> 01:01:53.350
nor should I tell,
but I will do it.

01:01:53.350 --> 01:01:56.304
As you may recall, we didn't
get to see Kim Jong-un.

01:01:56.304 --> 01:01:57.762
But on the day we
thought we might,

01:01:57.762 --> 01:01:59.824
we were instead brought
to the Palace of the Sun.

01:01:59.824 --> 01:02:01.240
Palace of the Sun
is the mausoleum

01:02:01.240 --> 01:02:03.780
where King Jong-il and
Kim Il-sung are actually

01:02:03.780 --> 01:02:05.545
laid out in state, embalmed.

01:02:05.545 --> 01:02:07.170
They get the Madame
Tussauds treatment.

01:02:07.170 --> 01:02:08.160
I didn't know that.

01:02:08.160 --> 01:02:09.630
So I'll jump to
the chase and say

01:02:09.630 --> 01:02:11.530
after seeing the
entire mausoleum,

01:02:11.530 --> 01:02:14.740
you get brought into the actual
moment where Kim Jong-il is

01:02:14.740 --> 01:02:16.390
laying there,
bathed in red light.

01:02:16.390 --> 01:02:18.040
You're surrounded
by military police.

01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:20.665
We happened to be there on a day
when only military police were

01:02:20.665 --> 01:02:23.280
also allowed to visit, so
we kind of got separated.

01:02:23.280 --> 01:02:25.580
We ended up being with
our own essentially troops

01:02:25.580 --> 01:02:27.170
and military police going in.

01:02:27.170 --> 01:02:30.422
You're supposed bow at
the side, bow at the feet,

01:02:30.422 --> 01:02:32.380
walk around the head and
bow at the other side.

01:02:32.380 --> 01:02:33.960
We didn't bow, but
the military did.

01:02:33.960 --> 01:02:37.755
And as they bowed, I was staring
across Jim Jong-il's nose,

01:02:37.755 --> 01:02:39.640
and Eric Schmidt is on
the other side of it.

01:02:39.640 --> 01:02:44.080
And he kind of looks to
the side, stares at me,

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:46.210
and at the absurdity
of the situation,

01:02:46.210 --> 01:02:50.320
I got the worst fifth
grade giggle fit.

01:02:50.320 --> 01:02:53.495
I just close my eyes and
just every muscle tensed,

01:02:53.495 --> 01:02:57.847
and thought I cannot
start laughing now.

01:02:57.847 --> 01:02:58.930
There are military please.

01:02:58.930 --> 01:03:00.870
There are 50 military
police around here,

01:03:00.870 --> 01:03:03.710
and I'm pretty sure I would
have been this escorted away.

01:03:03.710 --> 01:03:04.910
But I just thought as I was
staring across your nose--

01:03:04.910 --> 01:03:06.600
ERIC SCHMIDT: And this
is their most sacred site

01:03:06.600 --> 01:03:07.224
in North Korea.

01:03:07.224 --> 01:03:08.345
KEVIN BLEYER: Absolutely.

01:03:08.345 --> 01:03:11.280
ERIC SCHMIDT: I
hope in our hour,

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:14.940
you got a sense of why we've
become such good friends.

01:03:14.940 --> 01:03:16.640
And it's a bit of
advice for all of you.

01:03:16.640 --> 01:03:19.620
If you ever find yourself in
a foreign country with five

01:03:19.620 --> 01:03:21.560
or six fellow
travelers, turn off

01:03:21.560 --> 01:03:22.806
your devices a little while.

01:03:22.806 --> 01:03:25.180
Get to know them because
they're going to be fascinating.

01:03:25.180 --> 01:03:26.440
We've had such a good time.

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:27.510
Thank you for this.

01:03:27.510 --> 01:03:31.010
Thank you for coming, and
thank you all for coming.

01:03:31.010 --> 01:03:31.510
GOV.

01:03:31.510 --> 01:03:33.210
BILL RICHARDSON: Thank you.

01:03:33.210 --> 01:03:34.885
ERIC SCHMIDT: Thank you.

